<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-03-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-03-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="685" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d685">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/6663: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner at Constantinople</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bristol</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-03-27"><hi rend="italic">March 27, 1920</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received March 31—7:10
                                    a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>236. Following from McCully, Novorossiisk:</p>
                            <p>34. March 27, noon. Red forces occupied Novorossiisk 10 a.m. to-day
                                after some fighting in eastern part of town in which, besides land
                                forces, only Russian destroyers took part. Large portion Volunteer
                                army was evacuated to Crimea but several thousand joined Red forces
                                and others retreated east coast of Black Sea. All vessels have <pb facs="0690" n="590" xml:id="pg_590"/> gone to sea, British and
                                French being fired on by artillery but care was taken apparently not
                                to fire on <hi rend="italic">Galveston</hi> which was closer in and
                                last to leave. McCully.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bristol</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>